  "prompt": "A triangle has angles in the ratio 2:3:4. What is the size of the smallest of the three angles?",
  "response": "Let the angles of the triangle be represented by \\(2x\\), \\(3x\\), and \\(4x\\) based on the given ratio of 2:3:4. The sum of the angles in a triangle is always \\(180^\\circ\\).\n\nWe can set up the equation:\n\n\\[\n2x + 3x + 4x = 180^\\circ\n\\]\n\nCombining the terms gives:\n\n\\[\n9x = 180^\\circ\n\\]\n\nNow, we solve for \\(x\\):\n\n\\[\nx = \\frac{180^\\circ}{9} = 20^\\circ\n\\]\n\nNow we can find the sizes of the angles:\n\n1. The first angle is \\(2x = 2 \\times 20^\\circ = 40^\\circ\\).\n2. The second angle is \\(3x = 3 \\times 20^\\circ = 60^\\circ\\).\n3. The third angle is \\(4x = 4 \\times 20^\\circ = 80^\\circ\\).\n\nThe smallest angle among \\(40^\\circ\\), \\(60^\\circ\\), and \\(80^\\circ\\) is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{40^\\circ}\n\\]",
